    <a href="/reading/geometry/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to geometry</a>

    <h1>Power Diagrams</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Wikipedia (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_diagram"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Power diagram</a>) &middot; <a href="https://june.kim/power-diagrams-ad-auctions"><img src="/reading/jk.png" alt="jk" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>june.kim</a> &middot; CC BY-SA 4.0</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">A <strong>power diagram</strong> is a weighted Voronoi diagram. Each site has a weight (think: radius of influence). The cell of a site contains all points where the <strong>power distance</strong> to that site is smallest. The boundary between two cells is still a hyperplane, but it shifts toward the lighter site. This is the geometry behind ad auctions.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. Power of a point -->
    <h3>Power of a point</h3>
    <p>The <strong>power</strong> of a point x with respect to a circle centered at p with radius r is d(x, p)&sup2; - r&sup2;. If the point is outside the circle, the power is positive. On the circle, zero. Inside, negative. The power equals the squared length of the tangent from x to the circle. When r = 0, power reduces to squared Euclidean distance, and the power diagram becomes the ordinary Voronoi diagram.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Power of a point with respect to a circle
; pow(x, (center, radius)) = d(x, center)^2 - radius^2

(define (dist-sq p q)
  (+ (* (- (car p) (car q)) (- (car p) (car q)))
     (* (- (cadr p) (cadr q)) (- (cadr p) (cadr q)))))

(define (power-of-point x center radius)
  (- (dist-sq x center) (* radius radius)))

; Circle centered at (3, 3) with radius 2
(define center (list 3 3))
(define r 2)

; Test points
(for-each
  (lambda (x)
    (let ((pw (power-of-point x center r)))
      (display "pow(") (display x) (display ") = ")
      (display pw)
      (display (cond ((> pw 0) " (outside)")
                     ((= pw 0) " (on circle)")
                     (else     " (inside)")))
      (newline)))
  (list (list 3 3)    ; center -> -4
        (list 5 3)    ; on circle -> 0
        (list 6 3)    ; outside -> 5
        (list 3 4)))  ; inside -> -3
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`def power_of_point(x, center, radius):
    d_sq = sum((a-b)**2 for a,b in zip(x, center))
    return d_sq - radius**2

center, r = (3, 3), 2

for x in [(3,3), (5,3), (6,3), (3,4)]:
    pw = power_of_point(x, center, r)
    status = "outside" if pw > 0 else "on circle" if pw == 0 else "inside"
    print(f"pow({x}) = {pw} ({status})")
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 2. Power cells -->
    <h3>Power cells</h3>
    <p>Given weighted sites (p_i, w_i), the power cell of site i is the set of points x where d(x, p_i)&sup2; - w_i is minimal. Larger weight means a larger cell. A site with zero weight gets the same cell as in the Voronoi diagram. A site with very large weight dominates nearby territory.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Nearest site by power distance (weighted Voronoi)
; power-dist(x, site_i) = d(x, p_i)^2 - w_i

(define (dist-sq p q)
  (+ (* (- (car p) (car q)) (- (car p) (car q)))
     (* (- (cadr p) (cadr q)) (- (cadr p) (cadr q)))))

(define (power-dist x site)
  (let ((center (car site)) (weight (cdr site)))
    (- (dist-sq x center) weight)))

; Three weighted sites: (center . weight)
(define sites
  (list (cons (list 2 2) 1)    ; light
        (cons (list 6 2) 9)    ; heavy — larger cell
        (cons (list 4 5) 4)))  ; medium

(define (nearest-power x sites)
  (let loop ((best (car sites))
             (best-pw (power-dist x (car sites)))
             (rest (cdr sites)))
    (if (null? rest) best
        (let ((pw (power-dist x (car rest))))
          (if (< pw best-pw)
              (loop (car rest) pw (cdr rest))
              (loop best best-pw (cdr rest)))))))

(for-each
  (lambda (x)
    (let ((s (nearest-power x sites)))
      (display "Query ") (display x)
      (display " -> site at ") (display (car s))
      (display " (w=") (display (cdr s)) (display ")") (newline)))
  (list (list 1 1) (list 4 2) (list 5 1) (list 3 4) (list 7 3)))
; Heavy site (6,2) with w=9 claims more territory
`} />


    <!-- SVG: Two weighted points with power diagram boundary -->
    <h3>The boundary shifts toward the lighter site</h3>
    <p>Between two sites, the power diagram boundary is still a hyperplane (a line in 2D). But unlike Voronoi, it is not the perpendicular bisector. It shifts toward the lighter site. The heavier site pushes the boundary away from itself, claiming more territory. When both weights are equal, you recover the Voronoi boundary.</p>

    <div class="flex justify-center my-6">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 400 200" class="w-full max-w-md" style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;">
        <!-- Left site: small weight -->
        <circle cx="120" cy="100" r="20" fill="none" stroke="#60a5fa" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-opacity="0.4"/>
        <circle cx="120" cy="100" r="3" fill="#60a5fa" fill-opacity="0.8"/>
        <text x="120" y="140" text-anchor="middle" fill="#60a5fa" font-size="11" fill-opacity="0.7">w = 1</text>

        <!-- Right site: large weight -->
        <circle cx="280" cy="100" r="45" fill="none" stroke="#f59e0b" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-opacity="0.4"/>
        <circle cx="280" cy="100" r="3" fill="#f59e0b" fill-opacity="0.8"/>
        <text x="280" y="155" text-anchor="middle" fill="#f59e0b" font-size="11" fill-opacity="0.7">w = 9</text>

        <!-- Voronoi boundary (midpoint = 200): faint dashed -->
        <line x1="200" y1="20" x2="200" y2="180" stroke="#71717a" stroke-width="0.7" stroke-opacity="0.45" stroke-dasharray="4,4"/>
        <text x="200" y="15" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="9" fill-opacity="0.3">Voronoi</text>

        <!-- Power boundary: shifted toward light site -->
        <!-- pow boundary: d(x,p1)^2 - w1 = d(x,p2)^2 - w2 -->
        <!-- midpoint of (120,280) = 200, shift = (w2-w1)/(2*dist) = (9-1)/(2*160) = 0.025 * 160 = shifted by 25 toward light -->
        <line x1="175" y1="20" x2="175" y2="180" stroke="#a78bfa" stroke-width="2" stroke-opacity="0.6"/>
        <text x="175" y="192" text-anchor="middle" fill="#a78bfa" font-size="9" fill-opacity="0.6">Power boundary</text>

        <!-- Arrow showing shift direction -->
        <line x1="198" y1="170" x2="178" y2="170" stroke="#a78bfa" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity="0.4"/>
        <polygon points="178,167 172,170 178,173" fill="#a78bfa" fill-opacity="0.4"/>
        <text x="188" y="182" text-anchor="middle" fill="#a78bfa" font-size="8" fill-opacity="0.4">shift</text>

        <!-- Background shading -->
        <rect x="0" y="20" width="175" height="160" fill="#60a5fa" fill-opacity="0.03"/>
        <rect x="175" y="20" width="225" height="160" fill="#f59e0b" fill-opacity="0.03"/>
      </svg>
    </div>


    <!-- 4. Ad auctions connection -->
    <h3>The geometry of ad auctions</h3>
    <p>In a second-price ad auction, each bidder has a position (relevance score) and a bid (weight). The winning bidder for a query is the one with the smallest power distance. The bid shifts the boundary: a higher bid captures more query territory, exactly like a heavier site in the power diagram. The price paid is determined by the boundary location, not the bid itself. This is the geometric view of the generalized second-price auction.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Ad auction as power diagram
; Each advertiser: (relevance-vector . bid)
; Power distance to query q: d(q, relevance)^2 - bid
; Winner = smallest power distance = highest "score"

(define (dist-sq p q)
  (+ (* (- (car p) (car q)) (- (car p) (car q)))
     (* (- (cadr p) (cadr q)) (- (cadr p) (cadr q)))))

; Advertisers: ((relevance-x relevance-y) . bid)
(define advertisers
  (list (cons (list 3 5) 2)    ; Advertiser A: relevant to (3,5), bid 2
        (cons (list 7 3) 8)    ; Advertiser B: relevant to (7,3), bid 8
        (cons (list 5 8) 5)))  ; Advertiser C: relevant to (5,8), bid 5

(define (power-score query advertiser)
  ; Lower power = wins (like Voronoi nearest)
  (- (dist-sq query (car advertiser)) (cdr advertiser)))

(define (auction-winner query advertisers)
  (let loop ((best (car advertisers))
             (best-pw (power-score query (car advertisers)))
             (rest (cdr advertisers)))
    (if (null? rest) best
        (let ((pw (power-score query (car rest))))
          (if (< pw best-pw)
              (loop (car rest) pw (cdr rest))
              (loop best best-pw (cdr rest)))))))

(for-each
  (lambda (q)
    (let ((w (auction-winner q advertisers)))
      (display "Query ") (display q) (display " -> ")
      (display "Advertiser at ") (display (car w))
      (display " (bid=") (display (cdr w)) (display ")") (newline)))
  (list (list 3 5) (list 6 3) (list 5 7) (list 4 4)))
; Higher bids push boundaries, claiming more query territory
`} />


